					Shiele of the Educational Department of Henry Disston &amp; Sons 
					give an excellent talk on the development of saws and saw 
					making.&nbsp; Incidentally he explained how the little &quot;nib&quot; 
					near the lower end of the handsaw came to be placed there.&nbsp; 
					Later when I received my September number of Educational 
					Handwork I found that this little &quot;nib&quot; was the cause of 
					scientific research and much speculation in England.&nbsp; 
					This information came thru the following article written by 
					H. Williams Smith of London:</p>
					<p align="left"><b>An Answer for an Oft-Asked Question</b></p>
					<p align="left" class="body">I don't guarantee that the 
					answer is the correct one, but it is more satisfactory to me 
					than any I have yet obtained.&nbsp; I have awaited a 
					satisfactory answer for many years, but I have never felt 
					impatient for one.&nbsp; Whenever a boy has asked me, 
					&quot;Please, sir, what is that little bit sticking up on the 
					back of the saw for?&quot; I have always felt a kind of pleasure 
					in confessing my ignorance.</p>
					<p align="left" class="body">We teachers have to know so 
					much, and have to give the impression that we know so much 
					more than we do know (by which I do not imply any deception, 
					but mean an impression of prescience and profundity, which 
					even on inspectors has been known not to be without effect) 
					that sometimes it is not merely refreshing, but absolutely 
					necessary to declare, &quot;I don't know.&quot; <br>
					You need to be very careful how you confess ignorance to 
					your pupils (as careful as a judge on the bench, certainly) 
					but when you can do so safely, the effect is beneficial.&nbsp; 
					The pupil thereby receives proof that you are made of the 
					same clay as himself, and feels more kindly disposed to you 
					when he realizes that you are by way of being a human being 
					after all. Well, up to a very recent date, I really took 
					some solace in being unable to give an answer to the 
					question so frequently asked.</p>
					<p align="left" class="body">Now, I shall have to fall back 
					for refreshment on something else of which I am profoundly 
					ignorant, nor do I anticipate much difficulty in finding it.</p>
					<p align="left" class="body">I have, of course, tried to 
					find out what that little bit was sticking up for, and 
					particularly when I hurt one of ray fingers with it.&nbsp; I 
					have noticed Disston and other American makers have omitted 
					it, and I concluded by this that it must be of hoary 
					antiquity, such as a brand new country could not tolerate.&nbsp; 
					When I paid a visit to Sheffield, and got into conversation 
					with the very intelligent representative of a justly-famous 
					and esteemed firm of tool-makers, I deemed that my question 
					would at last be answered. So I said to the Sheffield man, 
					&quot;Why do you continue to make that little projection on the 
					back of the saw?&quot;&nbsp; And he said, &quot;Blest, if I know. I 
					suppose because our great grandfathers did it.</p>
					<p align="left" class="body">&quot;After this rebuff, I ceased to 
					entertain hopes of ever solving the mystery. I was intensely 
					interested, therefore, to read in a recent issue of the 
					local newspaper of my district, that before the Hampstead 
					Scientific Society Prof. Flinders Petrie, the president of 
					that society, had lectured on &quot;The Development of Tools and 
					Weapons,&quot; and that Prof.&nbsp; Arthur Dendy, F. R. S., the 
					vice-president, after the lecture, said, &quot;he was 
					particularly interested in the nick still made at the narrow 
					end of a saw, referred to by Prof. Petrie, the vestige of 
					the hole that was once put there for hanging up the tool.&quot;</p>
					<p align="left" class="body">This constitutes a very pretty 
					little episode. We Hampstead people take no discount even 
					from Boston in our appreciation of and endeavor towards 
					culture, and we think nothing so humble as to be not worth 
					our while to understand. So we are glad to have Prof. Petrie 
					tell us about the nick, and we are glad, too, to find that 
					Prof. Dendy, like ourselves, has been worried about the 
					matter.</p>
					<p align="left" class="body">So now I shall tell my boys 
					exactly why that little nick is in the saw; and I shall go 
					on telling them, until more professors shall arise to cast 
					contumely and scorn on Prof. Petrie's theory, and to declare 
					that the tiny tooth is an undoubted survival of some other 
					convenience now fallen into desuetude.</p>
					<p align="left" class="body">Almost immediately after 
					reading this article I wrote to Henry Disston &amp; Sons for a 
					written verification of Mr. Schiele's statement. In this 
					letter I referred to the English belief that the &quot;nib&quot; was a 
					vestige of the hole that was once put there for hanging up 
					the tool.&nbsp; The reply contained the following: &quot;In our 
					experience of over seventy-six years of saw making, we have 
					never heard this explanation.&nbsp; As stated to you by Mr. 
					Scheele, this small nib or projection, is placed at the back 
					of a straightback saw near the end to break the straight 
					line and slightly to enhance the appearance of the saw.&quot;</p>
					<p align="left" class="body">Then came a later number of the 
					English magazine in which was the following letter and 
					illustration:</p>
					<blockquote>
						<p align="left" class="body"><i>Dear Mr. Editor:</i></p>
						<p align="left" class="body"><i>Re Mr. H. Williams Smith's 
					article on &quot;An Answer for the Oft-asked Question'' in your 
					September number, I am always glad to see questions of this 
					kind raised, and I am sure my friend Mr. Smith will not mind 
					my airing my views on the matter.</i></p>
						<p align="left" class="body"><i>The history of our woodworking 
					tools is too often looked upon as being complete; yet how 
					many of our handwork teachers have any real grip of the 
					subject? I feel that we have been handicapped by the fact 
					that this particular branch of history has been left to 
					ethnologists who have only dealt with tools in so far as 
					they assist research dealing with the history of man. <br>The suggestion of Prof. Arthur Dendy, F. R. S. as quoted by 
					Mr. Smith, may have some claim to consideration, but seeing 
					that saws of this type can always be hung by their handles, 
					(a position which I think would be invariably more 
					convenient), I doubt if his is the true solution of the 
					problem. </i></p>
						<p align="left" class="body"><i>I am more disposed to favor the 
					solution of the Sheffield man, namely, that it is &quot;Because 
					our great-grandfathers did it.&quot;&nbsp; Unfortunately he did 
					not state why they did it.&nbsp; I therefore submit a 
					possible reason for such a practice. </i></p>
					</blockquote>
					<p align="center">
					<img border="1" src="0_img/1917-ManualTraining%20Mag.jpg" width="560" height="522"></p>
					<blockquote>
						<p align="left" class="body"><i>Firstly, our grandparents took 
					far greater pride in their tools than is common amongst the 
					workmen of today.&nbsp; Secondly, as is common in the 
					country to-day, tools had to be carried in a handle offered 
					a convenient place to which to tie the string; at the other 
					end, due to the taper of the blade, it would need some means 
					for preventing the string becoming loose and slipping off, 
					hence the little nick. (See diagram No. 2.) </i></p>
						<p align="left" class="body"><i>Some of Disston's saws would 
					need no such device, the taper usually ceasing before 
					reaching the end of the blade. (See diagram No. 3.) </i></p>
						<p align="left" class="body"><i>Yours faithfully,</i></p>
						<p align="left" class="body"><i>SIDNEY A. SWITZER. </i>
						</p>
					</blockquote>
					<p align="left" class="body">About that time I saw Mr. 
					Schiele again and he told me that the Disston people fully 
					believe that the &quot;nib&quot; is and always has been an ornament 
					placed there by an early saw maker with feeling for design, 
					and then copied year after year.&nbsp; He referred me to the 
					statement in Disston's Handbook on Saws which reads thus: 
					The &quot;Nib&quot; near the end of a handsaw has no practical use 
					whatever, it merely serves to break the straight line of the 
					back of blade and is an ornamentation only.</p>
					<p align="left" class="body">CHAS. C. BRYANT<br>
&nbsp;</p>
							</td>
						</tr>
					</table>
				</div>

				</font>
